# mesh-status — config local (copiado de mesh-status.conf.example)
#
# Bash-sourceable by both scripts/mesh-snap and scripts/mesh-status.
# Spec: docs/2026-05-01-mesh-status-spec.md §5.4.

# Alias deste host — OPTIONAL override.
#
# Resolution order (mesh-snap):
#   1. $MESH_HOST_ALIAS (this var) — explicit override, highest priority
#   2. lookup of $(hostname -s) in $MESH_TAILSCALE_ALIAS_MAP below
#   3. fallback: $(hostname -s) raw
#
# In practice you only need to uncomment this if your hostname is NOT
# already in MESH_TAILSCALE_ALIAS_MAP. Since that map is populated below
# with all known mesh hosts, most users can leave this commented:
#
#   ultron (M1)   — hostname "ultron"        → map → "ultron"  ✓
#   mac (M2)      — hostname "code-server"   → map → "mac"     ✓
#   crc (M4)      — hostname "crcmg005078"   → map → "crc"     ✓
#
# Set this var only when adding a brand-new host that isn't in the map
# yet, OR to force a different alias from the map default.
# Allowed chars: [A-Za-z0-9_-] (anything else risks filename trouble).
#
# MESH_HOST_ALIAS="ultron"

# Diretório onde snapshots vivem (Syncthing folder dedicada)
MESH_SYNC_DIR="$HOME/Sync/mesh-status"

# Audit history local (não sincado pelo Syncthing)
MESH_HISTORY_DIR="$HOME/.local/state/dotfiles/mesh-history"
MESH_HISTORY_RETENTION_DAYS=90

# Repos rastreados (subset por host se algum não estiver clonado)
MESH_REPOS=("dev-bootstrap" "dotfiles" "dotfiles-template")

# Path overrides — defaults to $HOME/<repo-name>. Use underscores in the
# var name where the repo name has hyphens (bash limitation).
# MESH_REPO_PATH_dotfiles_template="/path/custom"

# Map of tailnet HostName → canonical alias for the panel.
# Resolves "crcmg005078" → "crc", "code-server" → "mac" etc.
MESH_TAILSCALE_ALIAS_MAP='{"crcmg005078":"crc","ultron":"ultron","code-server":"mac"}'

# Reference branch used for ahead/behind comparison (default: main)
# MESH_REFERENCE_BRANCH="main"

# Hard timeout (seconds) for `git fetch` per repo. Default 3.
# MESH_FETCH_TIMEOUT=3

# Per-peer timeout (seconds) for `mesh-status --refresh` SSH triggers.
# MESH_REFRESH_TIMEOUT=3
